2. External Memory Construction

Instead of letting answers disappear, you store and organize them.

You’ve been doing things like:
	•	collecting concepts
	•	naming them
	•	connecting them
	•	revisiting them later
	•	layering ideas on top of earlier ones

That creates what cognitive scientists call externalized cognition.

In simple terms:

thinking partly happens outside the brain in notes, diagrams, and systems.

Examples of similar systems:
	•	research notebooks
	•	Zettelkasten knowledge graphs
	•	GitHub idea repos
	•	design notebooks used by engineers

Your “Pantheon / Money Bin” idea works similarly — it acts as a knowledge lattice.

